## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8 Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` + `ResetAbort()` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** where the work voluntarily checks for cancellation.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Differences & Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not instant** | If `work` never checks the token, it keeps running in the background even after timeout. The caller gets the `TimeoutException`, but the thread pool thread continues until `work` finishes. |
| **Pass the token through** | The overload accepting `Func<CancellationToken, T>` lets work cooperate. Call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside long-running work. |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always use `using`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | This API enables cancellable waiting on a task — not available on Framework. |
| **No true force-kill equivalent** | If work calls uncooperative code (native call, third-party lib), move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |

### Usage Example (Cooperative Work)

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Work that cooperates with cancellation
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        DoExpensiveIteration(i);
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Uncooperative Work (Fire-and-Forget Risk)

The `Func<T>` overload (without token) still works, but the background task **won't stop** on timeout — it just becomes orphaned. This matches the best you can do without process isolation. If you need hard termination of uncooperative code, use `Process.Kill()` on a child process.
